I divided the big test cases size by 2.

For the complexity, I find it similar to "Heart of the city" or  "The crime scene" (which are both rated as very difficult)
It may look easy when reading the solution, but I do not think it is so easy to come up with it, as it requires combining several ideas (Pick's theorem, polygon area computation, as well as finding a not so trivial way to efficiently compute the number of points on sides).

I am not sure what makes you think this problem is "language library specific".
The only call to a c++ standard library function is the call to std::gcd which has equivalent in other languages (like math.gcd in python) and that can be computed with one line in any language anyway with Euclid algorithm:
int gcd(int a, int b) 
{
   return (b ? gcd(b, a % b) : a);
}
